<section xml:id="sec-logical-equivalence">
    <title>Logical Equivalences</title>
    <objectives xml:id="obj-logical-equivalences">
  <title>Goals for This Section</title>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Define <term>logical equivalence</term> and use truth tables to determine whether
      two statements are logically equivalent.
    </li>
    <li>
      Apply common equivalence laws, including <term>De Morgan’s Laws </term> and the
      double-negation law, to rewrite statements more simply.
    </li>
    <li>
      Learn how to negate statements involving conjunctions, disjunctions, and conditionals.
    </li>
  </ol>
</objectives>

<definition xml:id="def-lequivalence">
    <statement>
<p>
  Two statements are <term>logically equivalent</term> if they have the same truth value
  for every possible assignment of truth values to their variables. Equivalently, their truth tables have
  identical final columns. We use <m>\equiv</m> to denote logical equivalence between statements.
</p>

    </statement>
</definition>  
<example xml:id="example-double-negation-equivalence">
  <title><m> p \equiv \lnot(\lnot p)</m></title>

  <p>
    The following truth table shows that the statements
    <m>p</m> and <m>\lnot(\lnot p)</m> always have the same truth value.
    Therefore, they are logically equivalent,  thus 
    <me>
    p \equiv \lnot(\lnot p)
  </me>
  </p>

  <table>
    <title>Truth Table for <m>p</m> and <m>\lnot(\lnot p)</m></title>
    <tabular halign="center">
      <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
        <cell><m>p</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\lnot p</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\lnot(\lnot p)</m></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>T</cell>
        <cell>F</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>F</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
        <cell>F</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
  </table>

  <p>
    Since the columns for <m>p</m> and <m>\lnot(\lnot p)</m> are identical,
    we conclude that <m>p \equiv \lnot(\lnot p)</m>.
  </p>
</example>
<example xml:id="example-disjunction-commutative">
  <title><m>p \lor q \equiv q \lor p</m></title>

  <p>
    The following truth table shows that the statements
    <m>p \lor q</m> and <m>q \lor p</m> always have the same truth value.
    Therefore, they are logically equivalent.
  </p>

  <table>
    <title>Truth Table for <m>p \lor q</m> and <m>q \lor p</m></title>
    <tabular halign="center">
      <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
        <cell><m>p</m></cell>
        <cell><m>q</m></cell>
        <cell><m>p \lor q</m></cell>
        <cell><m>q \lor p</m></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>T</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>T</cell>
        <cell>F</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>F</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
        <cell>T</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>F</cell>
        <cell>F</cell>
        <cell>F</cell>
        <cell>F</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
  </table>

  <p>
    Since the columns for <m>p \lor q</m> and <m>q \lor p</m> are identical,
    we conclude that <m>p \lor q \equiv q \lor p</m>.
  </p>
</example>
<exercise xml:id="ex-equivalence-implication-disjunction">
  <title><me>p \to q \equiv (\lnot p)\lor q</me></title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that <m>p \to q</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\lor q</m> are logically equivalent.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We compare the truth values of <m>p \to q</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\lor q</m>
      for all possible truth values of <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>.
    </p>

    <table>
      <title>Truth Table Comparison</title>
      <tabular halign="center">
        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
          <cell><m>p</m></cell>
          <cell><m>q</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lnot p</m></cell>
          <cell><m>(\lnot p)\lor q</m></cell>
          <cell><m>p \to q</m></cell>
        </row>

        <row>
          <cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

    <p>
      The columns for <m>p \to q</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\lor q</m> are identical,
      so the two statements are logically equivalent.
      Thus, <m>p \to q \equiv (\lnot p)\lor q</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>
