</exercise>
<remark xml:id="remark-demorgan-laws">
  <title>De Morgan’s Laws</title>

  <p>
    De Morgan’s Laws describe how negation interacts with conjunction
    and disjunction. They state that negating a compound statement changes
    <term>and</term> to <term>or</term>, and <term>or</term> to <term>and</term>,
    while negating each individual statement.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="example-demorgan-and">
    <title>Negation of a Conjunction</title>
    <p>
      The statement <m>\lnot(p \land q)</m> is logically equivalent to
      <m>(\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m>.
    </p>
    <md>
      \lnot(p \land q) \equiv (\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)
    </md>
      <p>
    We use truth tables to verify this De Morgan’s Law by comparing the truth values
    of each pair of statements.
  </p>


  <table>
    <title>Truth Table for <m>\lnot(p \land q)</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m></title>
    <tabular halign="center">
      <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
        <cell><m>p</m></cell>
        <cell><m>q</m></cell>
        <cell><m>p \land q</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\lnot(p \land q)</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\lnot p</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\lnot q</m></cell>
        <cell><m>(\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m></cell>
      </row>

      <row><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
      <row><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
      <row><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
      <row><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
    </tabular>
  </table>

  <p>
    The columns for <m>\lnot(p \land q)</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m>
    are identical, so
    <m>\lnot(p \land q)\equiv(\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m>.
  </p>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="example-demorgan-or">
    <title>Negation of a Disjunction</title>
    <p>
      The statement <m>\lnot(p \lor q)</m> is logically equivalent to
      <m>(\lnot p)\land(\lnot q)</m>.
    </p>
    <md>
      \lnot(p \lor q) \equiv (\lnot p)\land(\lnot q)
    </md>
     <table>
    <title>Truth Table for <m>\lnot(p \lor q)</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\land(\lnot q)</m></title>
    <tabular halign="center">
      <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
        <cell><m>p</m></cell>
        <cell><m>q</m></cell>
        <cell><m>p \lor q</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\lnot(p \lor q)</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\lnot p</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\lnot q</m></cell>
        <cell><m>(\lnot p)\land(\lnot q)</m></cell>
      </row>

      <row><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
      <row><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
      <row><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
      <row><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
    </tabular>
  </table>

  <p>
    Since the final columns match, we conclude that
    <m>\lnot(p \lor q)\equiv(\lnot p)\land(\lnot q)</m>.
  </p>
  </example>

</remark>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-exercises-logical-equivalence">
  <title>Exercises</title>

  <p>
    Determine whether each pair of statements is logically equivalent.  Justify your
    answer by using truth tables.
  </p>

  <question xml:id="q-equiv-a">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine whether <m>p\lor(p\land q)</m> and <m>p</m> are logically equivalent.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <table>
        <title>Truth Table for <m>p\lor(p\land q)</m> and <m>p</m></title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
            <cell><m>p</m></cell>
            <cell><m>q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>p\land q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>p\lor(p\land q)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>p</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The final two columns are identical, so <m>p\lor(p\land q)\equiv p</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </question>

  <question xml:id="q-equiv-b">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine whether <m>\lnot(p\lor q)</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m>
        are logically equivalent.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <table>
        <title>Truth Table for <m>\lnot(p\lor q)</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m></title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
            <cell><m>p</m></cell>
            <cell><m>q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>p\lor q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\lnot(p\lor q)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\lnot p</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\lnot q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The columns for <m>\lnot(p\lor q)</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\lor(\lnot q)</m>
        are <term>not</term>identical, so they are logically equivalent.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </question>

  <question xml:id="q-equiv-c">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine whether <m>\lnot(p\to q)</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\to(\lnot q)</m>
        are logically equivalent.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <table>
        <title>Truth Table for <m>\lnot(p\to q)</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\to(\lnot q)</m></title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
            <cell><m>p</m></cell>
            <cell><m>q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>p\to q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\lnot(p\to q)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\lnot p</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\lnot q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(\lnot p)\to(\lnot q)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>F</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell><cell>T</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The columns for <m>\lnot(p\to q)</m> and <m>(\lnot p)\to(\lnot q)</m> are not identical
        (for example, when <m>p=F</m> and <m>q=T</m>), so the statements are not logically equivalent.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </question>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-negating-statements">
  <title>Negating Statements</title>

  <p>
    Negating a statement means forming a new statement that is true exactly when
    the original statement is false. For compound statements, negation must be
    handled carefully.
  </p>

  <p>
    In particular, negating conjunctions and disjunctions follows
    <term>De Morgan’s Laws</term>, which were justified earlier using truth tables.
    See <xref ref="remark-demorgan-laws"/> for the formal statements.
  </p>

  <p>
    Negating conditional statements behaves differently and is a common source of
    confusion. The difference between a conditional and its reversal was explored
    in <xref ref="ex-equivalence-conditional-reversal"/>.
  </p>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-negating-english">
    <title>Negate the following Statements in English</title>

   

    <task xml:id="task-negate-simple">
      <statement>
        <p>We enjoy MATH.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We do not enjoy MATH.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="task-negate-conjunction">
      <statement>
        <p>We enjoy MATH and pizza.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We do not enjoy MATH or we do not enjoy pizza.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="task-negate-disjunction">
      <statement>
        <p>We enjoy MATH or pizza.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We do not enjoy MATH and we do not enjoy pizza.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task xml:id="task-negate-conditional">
      <statement>
        <p>If we enjoy MATH, then we enjoy pizza.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We enjoy MATH and we don't enjoy pizza.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    These examples illustrate how negation interacts with <term>and</term>,
    <term>or</term>, and <term>if, then </term>. This behavior is precisely described by De Morgan’s Laws.
  </p>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-exercise">
  <title>Exercise</title>


